3
00:00:11,009 --> 00:00:14,041
What is the trajectory
a charged particle

4
00:00:14,041 --> 00:00:16,710
in given electric and magnetic fields?

5
00:00:17,290 --> 00:00:20,535
In the past module
we focused our attention

6
00:00:20,535 --> 00:00:22,895
on the simplest possible scenario,

7
00:00:22,895 --> 00:00:27,339
that is the one of a constant,
uniform magnetic field.

8
00:00:27,781 --> 00:00:33,534
We will now turn our attention
to more complicated settings.

9
00:00:33,534 --> 00:00:38,922
We will first consider the one
of a constant electric and magnetic field,

10
00:00:39,201 --> 00:00:41,394
and then we will turn our attention

11
00:00:41,394 --> 00:00:44,704
to the case of a non-uniform
magnetic field.

12
00:00:46,420 --> 00:00:49,369
We've studied the trajectory
of a charged particle

13
00:00:49,369 --> 00:00:51,951
in a static uniform magnetic field.

14
00:00:51,951 --> 00:00:54,984
Let's complicate a little bit
the scenario.

15
00:00:54,984 --> 00:00:58,247
Let's add, on top of
the static uniform magnetic field,

16
00:00:58,247 --> 00:01:00,724
a static uniform electric field.

17
00:01:01,329 --> 00:01:05,744
How will a particle move
under the effect of these two forces?

18
00:01:05,744 --> 00:01:10,737
This is what we will see now,
but let me already anticipate

19
00:01:10,737 --> 00:01:13,514
that the result will be quite surprising.

20
00:01:14,874 --> 00:01:18,187
So what we want to solve
is a Newton equation

21
00:01:18,437 --> 00:01:21,222
of a particle with charge q,

22
00:01:21,796 --> 00:01:25,643
that is subject to
an electric and a magnetic field,

23
00:01:26,391 --> 00:01:30,370
with the electric and magnetic fields
that are constant.

24
00:01:32,073 --> 00:01:35,996
To approach this problem,
we will decompose these equations

25
00:01:35,996 --> 00:01:40,442
in a direction parallel and perpendicular
to the magnetic field.

26
00:01:40,442 --> 00:01:43,724
Let's start from the direction
parallel to the magnetic field.

27
00:01:44,956 --> 00:01:46,595
Along the parallel direction,

28
00:01:46,595 --> 00:01:50,288
we will have the mass
times the acceleration

29
00:01:51,546 --> 00:01:54,121
is equal to the parallel electric force,

30
00:01:55,060 --> 00:01:58,737
and of course the (v × B) force
will have no component

31
00:01:58,737 --> 00:02:00,814
in the parallel direction.

32
00:02:01,070 --> 00:02:02,155
What does it mean?

33
00:02:02,155 --> 00:02:05,864
Well, this is a very simple equation
to be solved,

34
00:02:05,864 --> 00:02:09,564
which gives us a uniformly
accelerated motion.

35
00:02:10,233 --> 00:02:13,575
The perpendicular direction is,
of course, more complicated.

36
00:02:14,456 --> 00:02:18,301
In this direction,
what we will have to solve is mass,

37
00:02:19,591 --> 00:02:23,795
times the acceleration
in the perpendicular direction,

38
00:02:24,262 --> 00:02:29,432
equal to the electric and magnetic force
taken in the perpendicular direction.

39
00:02:30,309 --> 00:02:34,130
So what is the motion
induced by these forces?

40
00:02:34,130 --> 00:02:37,308
Well, let's start to consider
a simple case.

41
00:02:37,597 --> 00:02:41,021
Let's imagine that we have
a magnetic field

42
00:02:41,021 --> 00:02:43,631
that comes out of this plane,

43
00:02:44,026 --> 00:02:48,359
and an electric field that points upwards.

44
00:02:49,361 --> 00:02:53,858
So let's place a particle,
a positively charged particle,

45
00:02:54,468 --> 00:02:56,195
q > 0

46
00:02:56,195 --> 00:02:59,492
and let's study the trajectory
of this particle,

47
00:02:59,492 --> 00:03:03,510
subject to these
electric and magnetic fields.

48
00:03:03,799 --> 00:03:05,493
Okay, the particle is at rest.

49
00:03:05,493 --> 00:03:08,945
The first thing that it will do
is that it will be accelerated

50
00:03:08,945 --> 00:03:11,725
by its electric field, upwards.

51
00:03:11,725 --> 00:03:14,526
Therefore the particle
will start to move upwards.

52
00:03:14,691 --> 00:03:18,448
At the same time,
it will be subject to the magnetic field,

53
00:03:18,448 --> 00:03:22,104
and therefore its trajectory
will be curved.

54
00:03:23,220 --> 00:03:26,847
And then the particle
will start to move down,

55
00:03:27,570 --> 00:03:32,792
and while moving downwards,
the electric field will slow it down.

56
00:03:33,394 --> 00:03:36,293
When its electric field slows it down,

57
00:03:36,293 --> 00:03:38,793
then the velocity decreases,

58
00:03:38,793 --> 00:03:40,943
and when the velocity decreases,

59
00:03:40,943 --> 00:03:44,370
the Larmor radius
of the particle decreases.

60
00:03:44,370 --> 00:03:51,311
Therefore the particle
subject to the magnetic force

61
00:03:51,311 --> 00:03:54,790
will move and will turn this way,

62
00:03:54,790 --> 00:03:57,808
and then will be accelerated again

63
00:03:57,808 --> 00:04:00,489
in the direction of the electric field.

64
00:04:01,152 --> 00:04:03,650
Again, larger Larmor radius,

65
00:04:04,106 --> 00:04:06,725
then the particle will move downwards,

66
00:04:06,725 --> 00:04:09,307
at the same time will be slowed down,

67
00:04:09,497 --> 00:04:12,396
and the Larmor radius
will become smaller

68
00:04:12,396 --> 00:04:15,155
and then the particles will come up...

69
00:04:16,024 --> 00:04:18,105
This will be the trajectory.

70
00:04:18,566 --> 00:04:22,666
If you want,
the guiding center of this particle

71
00:04:23,341 --> 00:04:26,557
will move in this direction,

72
00:04:26,863 --> 00:04:29,140
in a direction that is perpendicular

73
00:04:29,140 --> 00:04:32,768
to both the electric field,
and the magnetic field.

74
00:04:33,734 --> 00:04:38,008
Let's take the case of
negatively charged particles,

75
00:04:38,287 --> 00:04:40,192
that is initially at rest.

76
00:04:40,527 --> 00:04:44,885
Well, the particle will be accelerated
by the electric field,

77
00:04:45,130 --> 00:04:46,924
this time downwards,

78
00:04:47,583 --> 00:04:51,011
because the particle
is charged negatively.

79
00:04:51,418 --> 00:04:55,911
And then the particle will be subject
to the magnetic field.

80
00:04:55,911 --> 00:04:57,997
It will gyrate

81
00:04:58,480 --> 00:05:02,692
with a certain Larmor radius,
and then the particle

82
00:05:02,692 --> 00:05:06,281
because of the gyration will continue
to move it in this direction,

83
00:05:06,281 --> 00:05:10,551
