that is the classic expression
that we know.

244
00:18:20,027 --> 00:18:24,294
And therefore now, in the presence
of a force and a magnetic field,

245
00:18:24,294 --> 00:18:27,666
we will have a drift
that we can evaluate

246
00:18:27,666 --> 00:18:30,931
using the expression,
and will be given by,

247
00:18:31,964 --> 00:18:36,134
we'll call it vd, curvature drift,

248
00:18:36,830 --> 00:18:41,198
which is the centrifugal force × B,

249
00:18:41,702 --> 00:18:44,745
and using the expression
for centrifugal force,

250
00:18:44,745 --> 00:18:48,282
this will be given
by the following expression.

251
00:18:48,588 --> 00:18:52,697
This, as I was saying,
is what in plasma physics

252
00:18:52,697 --> 00:18:55,367
is called the curvature drift,

253
00:18:55,808 --> 00:19:01,130
and it's also an important quantity,
in plasma physics.

254
00:19:02,074 --> 00:19:06,945
Let's now consider the case
of a non-uniform magnetic field,

255
00:19:06,945 --> 00:19:11,319
one in which there is
a gradient of the magnetic field

256
00:19:11,319 --> 00:19:15,084
perpendicular to
the magnetic field itself.

257
00:19:15,625 --> 00:19:17,860
The scenario is therefore
the following one,

258
00:19:17,860 --> 00:19:21,748
we have a magnetic field
that points out of the plane,

259
00:19:21,748 --> 00:19:24,552
and which is subject to a gradient,

260
00:19:25,750 --> 00:19:29,705
in this direction,
perpendicular to B therefore.

261
00:19:33,062 --> 00:19:36,132
So let's suppose that
we have a charged particle.

262
00:19:38,270 --> 00:19:43,113
Let's suppose that
is positively charged.

263
00:19:43,113 --> 00:19:48,633
Now this particle may move,
and because of the v × B force

264
00:19:49,696 --> 00:19:51,735
will tend to gyrate,

265
00:19:52,501 --> 00:19:57,509
and while it starts to gyrate,
it will experience regions

266
00:19:57,509 --> 00:20:00,692
where the magnetic field
may become stronger,

267
00:20:00,692 --> 00:20:03,757
and when the magnetic field
may become stronger,

268
00:20:03,757 --> 00:20:06,840
the Larmor radius will become smaller.

269
00:20:07,528 --> 00:20:10,648
And then when the particle goes back

270
00:20:10,648 --> 00:20:15,392
it will experience regions
where the magnetic field is weaker,

271
00:20:15,392 --> 00:20:18,401
and therefore the Larmor radius is larger,

272
00:20:18,401 --> 00:20:24,123
and then again regions where
the magnetic field is stronger,

273
00:20:24,123 --> 00:20:28,207
and therefore
the Larmor radius smaller, etc.

274
00:20:28,578 --> 00:20:32,014
What is the result of such a motion?

275
00:20:32,402 --> 00:20:35,895
It is again, the one that can be described

276
00:20:35,895 --> 00:20:40,318
by the motion of the guiding center

277
00:20:40,318 --> 00:20:43,105
of the particle in this direction.

278
00:20:45,044 --> 00:20:49,785
Now, what is the velocity of the drift
of this guiding center?

279
00:20:49,785 --> 00:20:52,395
Well, the calculation
is fairly complicated,

280
00:20:52,395 --> 00:20:58,502
and you can find it in an appendix
to the present lecture.

281
00:20:58,502 --> 00:21:01,015
Here I will just give the result,

282
00:21:01,015 --> 00:21:04,761
it is what you actually
will need in the future.

283
00:21:04,761 --> 00:21:09,341
That is the v due to the gradient
of the magnetic field

284
00:21:09,341 --> 00:21:16,877
is equal to the mass
of the particle divided by 2B³

285
00:21:17,292 --> 00:21:21,806
v² of the particles, divided by the charge

286
00:21:22,967 --> 00:21:25,839
times the magnetic field

287
00:21:26,856 --> 00:21:30,275
cross the gradient of the magnetic field.

288
00:21:31,480 --> 00:21:34,953
As a matter of fact, as we see here,

289
00:21:34,953 --> 00:21:41,055
the guiding center with the drift,
on a direction that is perpendicular

290
00:21:41,055 --> 00:21:43,733
to both ∇B and B.

291
00:21:44,953 --> 00:21:47,907
This is what is called the <i>grad-B drift</i>.

292
00:21:51,024 --> 00:21:54,014
In the present module,
we have focused our attention

293
00:21:54,014 --> 00:22:00,072
on the trajectory of a particle
in a given electric and magnetic field.

294
00:22:00,072 --> 00:22:04,803
In the past lecture we had focused
our attention on a quite simple case,

295
00:22:04,803 --> 00:22:09,865
the one of a uniform
and constant magnetic field.

296
00:22:09,865 --> 00:22:14,253
Here we have considered
slightly more complicated cases.

297
00:22:14,253 --> 00:22:16,338
First of all, we have looked
at what happens

298
00:22:16,338 --> 00:22:20,919
when there is a constant
uniform electric and magnetic field,

299
00:22:20,919 --> 00:22:25,110
and then we have looked
at what is the particle trajectory

300
00:22:25,110 --> 00:22:28,907
when the magnetic field is non-uniform.

301
00:22:29,306 --> 00:22:31,710
We have pointed out that in all cases

302
00:22:31,710 --> 00:22:35,579
the particle trajectory can be described
as the superposition

303
00:22:35,579 --> 00:22:41,078
of a guiding center drift motion
plus a gyromotion,

304
00:22:41,078 --> 00:22:44,406
and we have given
the expression of this drift motion

305
00:22:44,406 --> 00:22:48,899
in all the relevant cases
that we have analyzed.
